CleanPlate — Secure Roommate Chore Coordinator
================================================

Standard library only. No pip install required.
Requires Python 3.10+ (for the X | None type hint syntax).

Platform: Linux / macOS. Tested on Ubuntu 22.04.
Run on the course VM: copy the folder, start the server, then run client commands.


QUICK START
-----------

  # Terminal 1: start the server
  ./cleanplate serve

  # Terminal 2: open the interactive shell
  ./cleanplate interactive
  cleanplate> signup alice
  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> create-household "42 Elm Street"
  cleanplate> household list
  cleanplate> exit

If the script is executable, you can also put the repo on your `PATH` and run
`cleanplate ...` directly.

PRIMARY USAGE
-------------

The intended way to use CleanPlate is as one continuous command session:

  ./cleanplate interactive

Inside the session, type regular commands without restarting the app each time:

  cleanplate> signup alice
  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> me
  cleanplate> create-household "Maple House"
  cleanplate> create-chore 1 "Take out trash"
  cleanplate> complete 4
  cleanplate> help
  cleanplate> exit

`shell` and `repl` are aliases for `interactive`.

ONE-SHOT MODE
-------------

You can still run single commands directly from your shell when needed:

`./cleanplate signup alice`
`./cleanplate login alice`
`./cleanplate passwd alice`
`./cleanplate me`
`./cleanplate create-household "Maple House"`
`./cleanplate create-chore 1 "Take out trash"`
`./cleanplate complete 4`

By default the client connects to http://127.0.0.1:8000.
To use a different server, set CLEANPLATE_SERVER_URL.


FULL COMMAND REFERENCE
----------------------

These commands work both inside `./cleanplate interactive` and as direct shell commands.

-- Identity & Access (Person 1) --
  ./cleanplate register   --username <name>
  ./cleanplate signup     <name>
  ./cleanplate login      --username <name>
  ./cleanplate login      <name>
  ./cleanplate reset-password --username <name>
  ./cleanplate passwd     <name>
  ./cleanplate logout
  ./cleanplate whoami
  ./cleanplate me

-- Household Management (Person 2) --
  ./cleanplate household create        --name "42 Elm St"
  ./cleanplate house create            "42 Elm St"
  ./cleanplate create-household        "42 Elm St"
  ./cleanplate household join          --code <invite_code>
  ./cleanplate join-household          <invite_code>
  ./cleanplate household show          --id <household_id>
  ./cleanplate household list
  ./cleanplate household rotate-invite --id <household_id>
  ./cleanplate household remove-member --id <household_id> --username bob

-- Chore Management (Person 3) --
  ./cleanplate chore create  --household <id> --title "Take out trash" [--due YYYY-MM-DD] [--assign bob]
  ./cleanplate create-chore  <id> "Take out trash" [--due YYYY-MM-DD] [--assign bob]
  ./cleanplate chore assign  --chore <id> --username bob
  ./cleanplate chore list    --household <id> [--status pending|complete|disputed] [--mine]
  ./cleanplate chore show    --chore <id>

-- Activity & Completion (Person 4) --
  ./cleanplate activity complete --chore <id>
  ./cleanplate complete          <id>
  ./cleanplate activity dispute  --chore <id> --reason "Floor still dirty"
  ./cleanplate activity resolve  --complaint <id> --outcome uphold|dismiss --note "..."
  ./cleanplate activity audit    --household <id>
  ./cleanplate audit             <household_id>
  ./cleanplate activity poll


EXAMPLE WALKTHROUGH
-------------------

  # Start one continuous command session
  ./cleanplate interactive

  # Two users register
  cleanplate> signup alice
  cleanplate> signup bob

  # Alice logs in and creates a household
  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> create-household "42 Elm Street"
  # → prints invite code, e.g. "Invite code: aB3xQr_kLmN"

  # Bob logs in and joins
  cleanplate> login bob
  cleanplate> join-household aB3xQr_kLmN

  # Bob can also join or create additional households later
  cleanplate> create-household "Weekend Cabin"
  cleanplate> household list

  # Alice (admin) creates and assigns a chore
  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> create-chore 1 "Vacuum living room" --assign bob --due 2025-04-10

  # Bob completes the chore
  cleanplate> login bob
  cleanplate> complete 1

  # Alice disputes it
  cleanplate> login alice
  cleanplate> activity dispute --chore 1 --reason "Missed under the couch"

  # Alice resolves her own dispute (uphold = bob must redo it)
  cleanplate> activity resolve --complaint 1 --outcome uphold --note "Please redo"

  # Anyone can view the audit log
  cleanplate> audit 1
  cleanplate> exit


FILE LAYOUT
-----------
  cleanplate      Shell wrapper for running the CLI
  main.py         Client entry point + server launcher
  client_cli.py   Client-side argparse handlers and HTTP calls
  api_client.py   JSON/HTTP client helper
  api_server.py   HTTP server exposing command handlers
  db.py           SQLite schema and query helpers          (server-side)
  session.py      Client file session + request session scope
  auth.py         Register, login, logout, whoami          [Person 1]
  households.py   Create, join, manage households          [Person 2]
  chores.py       Create, assign, list chores              [Person 3]
  activity.py     Complete, dispute, resolve, audit log    [Person 4]
  cleanplate.db  Created automatically on first run


ARCHITECTURE
------------

  Client:
    - main.py / client_cli.py
    - prompts the user, stores local session state, sends JSON requests

  Server:
    - api_server.py
    - runs the business logic modules and owns all database access

  Database:
    - SQLite remains on the server side only


SECURITY NOTES
--------------
  Passwords : hash password using scrypt,
              Parameters chosen per OWASP scrypt recommendations:
              N=2^14 (CPU/memory cost), r=8 (block size), p=1 (parallelism)
              Salt: 32 random bytes via secrets.token_bytes (CSPRNG).
              Output: "scrypt:<hex_salt>:<hex_hash>"

              Password strength checker follows these constraints:

              blacklisted passwords from:
              https://github.com/danielmiessler/SecLists/blob/master/Discovery/Web-Content/common.txt
              https://github.com/danielmiessler/SecLists/tree/master/Passwords

              minumum chars: 8

  Audit log : HMAC-SHA256 chained; verify_chain() detects any tampering.
  HMAC key  : Stored in DB for prototype; move to env var for alpha.
  Session   : ~/.cleanplate_session (chmod 600); cleared on logout.
  Auth      : Role check on every sensitive command, not just at login.

MULTI-HOUSEHOLD SUPPORT
-----------------------
  A single user account can belong to multiple households at the same time.
  Membership is tracked per (user_id, household_id), and most commands already
  scope actions by explicit household id or by the chore's household.
